<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Basically, there are 9 functions that MUST be covered in a 6-member dungeon-crawl (90% of the time, anyway):<P>1. Taunting (also involves Damage Absorbtion)<BR>2. Pulling<BR>3. Damage Dealing<BR>4. Primary Healing<BR>5. Mesmerisation<BR>6. Snaring<BR>7. Spell interruption (via Stuns and/or BASH)<BR>8. Rooting<BR>9. Evacuation<P>You might want to add SoW (which is a necessity for outdoors hunts), Track, Lockpick, and things of that nature to this list... however, they are more situation-specific. I'm mainly gunning for the things that you just about always need, for high-pull XP groups (since that's what everyone likes to talk about around here!  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> )<P>Here is a breakdown of which classes *can* fulfill each role. Although a given class may not be the *best* at something, it can adequately fulfill that role in a group:<P>Warrior: 1,2,3,7,(6 with Kunzar Ku'jusch)<BR>Monk: 2,3,(7 with some weapons)<BR>Rogue: 2,3,(6 with SBD)<P>Paladin: 1,2,3,7,8<BR>Shadow Knight: 1,2,3,6,7<BR>Ranger: 1,2,3,6,8<BR>Bard: 3,5,6<P>Cleric: 3,4,7,8,(6 with Regent Symbol of Innoruuk)<BR>Shaman: 3,4,8<BR>Druid: 3,4,6,7,8,9<P>Enchanter: 3,5,7,8<BR>Wizard: 3,6,7,8,9<BR>Magician: 3 (pets can cover 7 and 8, but not reliably enough)<BR>Necromancer: 3,5,6,8<P>So, of the 9 grouping essentials, wizards offer five--damage, snare, stun, root, and evacuation. The fact that they are not the best at a Sub-Set of ONE of these (set--damage; subset--consistent damage), does not mean the class is broken, especially when they ARE the best at the other subset of that same one (set--damage; subset--FAST damage). <P>I don't feel sorry for us wizards. I feel sorry for magicians. All they can do is damage, period. Sure, their pets can stun and root, but not as a means of reliable crowd control by any stretch of the imagination.<P>Anyway, I hope that puts things in perspective for ya. Wizards' largest threat is certainly not melee, IMHO... but rather druids. Druids sacrifice some of our damage-output, but in return they get two HUGE things--heals and damage shields, as well as SoW and Harmony if you're hunting outdoors, in addition to buffs, tracking, and DoTs. Personally, in my Übergroup, I would use the following setup:<P>Warrior<BR>Monk<BR>Rogue<BR>Enchanter<BR>Cleric<BR>Druid<P>That group has all 9 grouping essentials covered, in addition to nice things like track, lock-pick, harmony, SoW, and FD-pulling. The group I regularly hunt in is identical to the above, except we have ME (wohoo!!) in place of the monk. We absolutely rock! Sure, the net pace of GROUP damage output probably goes down by 5% or so, using me instead of a monk, but we have the added flexibility of having a backup evacuator, backup snarer, supa-fly nuker, primary rooter (to save the cleric/'chanter mana), and added stunner for those caster mobs (can never have too much stunning).<P>Anyway, I just wanted to offer a less theoretical, more practical overview of why wizards are a good class. Sure, wizards are not exactly what we all thought they would be when we started playing--then again, we're in Norrath, not Krynn!!  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"><P>Paz.<P>--------------------<P>51 Channeller :: Simryd "Your-target-resisted-Tishan's-Clash" L'Drael, Erudite Wizard of Quellious<BR>44 CLE :: Ulanji, High Elf Cleric of Tunare<BR>30 NEC :: Quokuus Jhuoroq, Human Plaguebringer of Bertoxxulous<BR>24 MNK :: Xodien Lo'Jong, Disciple of the Ashen Order<BR>14 SHD :: Sujata, Iksar Dark Knight of Cazic Thule<BR>12 RNG :: Kujatta, Human Patron of the Stormbringer<BR>*****************<BR>:: "Eschew Obfuscation" ::
</FONT>
