<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Thanks for the responses.<P>Woe, I guess it comes down to who is playing. I tried to be as objective as possible, given my experiences in EQ. Honestly, buffing is important, as you mentioned, but I left it out for one simple reason--every group must have some form of healer, and if you have a healer, you have some buffing, and that buffing will be adequate for most situations (exceptions: must have cleric buffs for raids), so the two are kinda paired up. I should probably have added it to item number 4, like so: Primary Healing and Buffing.<P>Also, 100% of the time, Snaring is super-critical. I can't over-emphasize this. Snaring is everything in dungeon hunting. It prevents adds. It prevents trains. It prevents wipeouts. Every group absolutely MUST have some form of snaring. If you're going to create a top 5, snaring has to be in there--I just don't see any way around that. I'm beginning to think that's the problem alot of wizards are having finding groups--you MUST think of yourself as a snarer. There have been many times (especially back when our group was just 5, before we added our druid), when I was the ONLY form of snare we had. That was of extreme *value* to the group.<P>Damage Shields--the wiz DS is 5 damage, for 5 minutes (not 2 as you suggested--time it on yourself sometime, it lasts as long as the lv 49 DRU Thorn spell). AND, it stacks with Thorns and the Mage Lava Shield. So... it helps, and if you get 3 fights in 5 min, there's a good chance it will be triggered 50 to 75 times, which means an additional 250 to 375 unresistable damage.<P>Slowing. You say you'd prefer to have a shammy slow so the 'chanter can concentrate on crowd control. That's a preference. Enchanters can slow every bit as well as shamans, and the group I hunt with utilizes the enchanter for this function. Slowing is very nice, but not 100% critical. What it does is save the healers' mana. I can see how you'd think it to be a group essential though. <P>As we discussed, there are essentials, and there are luxuries. I would place stat buffs, along with mana song, clarity, regeneration, damage shields, tracking, etc. into the category of luxuries. All of these enhance the functionality of the group, but do not make or break a group. A group can *function* without having these specific things accounted for.<P>OK, if we're going to totally simply things... honestly it boils down to variants of the following three things:<P>1. Damage Dealing <BR>2. Damage Prevention<P>Wizards are good at Damage Dealing. They are better than a majority of classes at Damage Dealing. They can dish it out faster than anyone else when necessary (people here seem to downplay the importance of this, it comes in VERY handy sometimes), and member-for-member they hold up their end on efficiency. Remember--the damage being dealt by the tanks is diluted, since their damage represents the Damage-Dealing contributions of both themselves and the classes healing and buffing them. A wizard in a WAR/CLE/WIZ 3-man-group only has to dish out HALF the damage of the WAR to hold up his end. Think about it. Of course, wizards usually sit somewhere closer to 70% to 80% of the average tank damage over time, which is fine, given the fact that they *can* unleash hell when needed.<P>Wizards are good at Damage Prevention. Stuns prevent damage. Evacs prevent Damage and downtime. Speed-kills via chain nukes prevent damage--a dead mob can't fight. Rooting prevents damage (a rooted mob breaks mez and just stands there glaring at the chanter). Snare prevents damage, by means of preventing adds and trains. Wizards are the only class that gets both a non-damaging root and a non-damaging snare. Think about that for a bit. In the standard mez/assist groups, you want someone other than the chanter casting a non-damaging root, and a wizard is the ONLY class that can do that AND cast a non-damaging snare. I never really thought about that until now!  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"> That's pretty cool, you just made me feel even better about wizards, hehe<P>Now, before you launch into a dissertation on how it is that all the other classes are somehow *better* at both of these things (although I welcome you to try), stop and think about the fact that a wizard is GOOD at all of these things. Let it settle a bit. Absorb it. Be one with it. Believe it. It's true, as much as you don't want to believe that it's true, it is.<P>The crusade to convince everyone that wizards are broken is lost on me. I find that the class offers a multi-faceted, enjoyable, valuable contribution to just about any group, and it's fun to play. The obsession with not doing the most damage is what gets ya down. A Mage with a pet will always outdamage a wizard. What if they didn't? You'd see maybe 2 Magicians on every server, and they'd be Verant employees.  <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"> The same is true of necros. <P>In my opinion, wizards make up for not being the most efficient damaging class by means of the other things they offer. I have found it to be true. Many of the high level guilds on my server have found it to be true. My hunting group finds it to be true. <P>Now, I'm off to do some do quad-kiting!  <IMG SRC="biggrin.gif" border="0"> Level 52 will be mine... oh yes--it shall be mine...<P>Paz.
</FONT>
